objects.name: Emotet
objects.description: Emotet is a highly active malware family that is often changing and modifying their attacks.

objects.name: Emotet epoch 5 infection on January 11th 2022
objects.description:
January 11th, Emotet spamming resumes. January 21st, Emotet emails are once again using attachments instead of links.

The new Emotet infrastructure is running on two separate botnets designated as epoch 4 and epoch 5. These designators are often abbreviated as E4 and E5.

objects.name: Emotet epoch 4 abusing App Installer on November 30th 2021
objects.description:
November 14th, new Emotet binary seen from Trickbot infections. November 15th, Emotet resumes spamming operations (emails have attachments). November 23rd, batch files noted during Emotet infection process. November 30th, Emotet starts abusing App Installer protocol.

The new Emotet infrastructure is running on two separate botnets designated as epoch 4 and epoch 5. These designators are often abbreviated as E4 and E5.

objects.name: Emotet Malware
objects.description:
December 7th, Cobalt strike seen in Emotet infections. December 21st, Emotet emails primarily used links to download initial Office document. New infection method with .hta files and PowerShell script are observed. 

January 11th, Emotet spamming resumes. January 21st, Emotet emails are once again using attachments instead of links.

The new Emotet infrastructure is running on two separate botnets designated as epoch 4 and epoch 5. These designators are often abbreviated as E4 and E5.

objects.name: Emotet epoch 4 infection on December 21st 2021
objects.description:

objects.name: Emotet epoch 4 activity on November 18th 2021
objects.description:
Emotet is one of the most prolific email-distributed malware families in our current threat landscape. Although a coordinated law enforcement effort shut down this malware in January 2021, Emotet resumed operations in November 2021. Since then, Emotet has returned to its status as a prominent threat.

The new Emotet infrastructure is running on two separate botnets designated as epoch 4 and epoch 5. These designators are often abbreviated as E4 and E5.
